title: Morality is as objective as Gravity
description:
Morality is about what we ought to do.
What we ought to do is in relation to goals.
Evolution gives us our goals.
Once a goal exists, an objectively best pathway to the goal also exists.
What we ought to do is navigate towards the goal along the objectively best pathway. 
Game theory is the study of how we calculate these objectively best pathways in complex social space.

title: Can Mormon Free Will rescue us from Atheistic Nihilism??
Nietzsche's Philosophy of the Individual (or lack thereof)
description:
Excerpt from:
HUMAN, ALL-TOO-HUMAN
Part 1, Section 50
"The soldier hopes to die on the field of battle for his victorious fatherland; for his loftiest desires triumph in the victory of his country. The mother gives to the child that of which she deprives herself - sleep, the best food, sometimes her health and fortune. But are all these un- egoistic conditions? Are these deeds of morality miracles, because, to use Schopenhauer's expression, they are 'impossible and yet performed'? Is it not clear that in all four cases the individual loves something of himself, a thought, a desire, a production, better than anything else of himself; that he therefore divides his nature and to one part sacrifices all the rest? Is it something entirely different when an obstinate man says, 'I would rather be shot than move a step out of my way for this man'? The desire for something (wish, inclination, longing) is present in all the instances mentioned; to give way to it, with all its consequences, is certainly not 'un-egoistic'.- In ethics man does not consider himself as individuum but as dividuum."

title: Credentist Epistemology: The Yin and Yang of Knowledge
description:
**Sorry for my posture - it is due to back pain**

Blog Link: https://transcendentphilos.wixsite.com/website/post/credentist-epistemology-the-yin-and-yang-of-knowledge

GPT summary: 
"Dive into a paradigm-shifting exploration of knowledge that challenges the very foundations of our understanding. "Credentist Epistemology: the Yin and Yang of Knowledge" unveils a controversial claim: absolute certainty is unattainable, and the traditional definitions of knowledge crumble in the face of skepticism. As we dissect the implications of skepticism and its impact on our perception of truth, a radical epistemological paradigm, credentism, emerges. Get ready for a journey that challenges everything you thought you knew about knowledge, truth, and the complexities of our existence.

The skeptics were onto something – truth is elusive and perhaps impossible to obtain. But what does this mean for knowledge? Can we truly possess knowledge if we cannot access an ultimate truth? Delve into the unsettling realization that our perceptions of reality may be mere glimpses into a deeper layer of existence. From questioning the reliability of our memories to challenging the consistency of natural laws, the article unravels the threads of certainty that hold our conventional views of knowledge together.

Traditional definitions, such as the classical knowledge model (JTB), face a formidable adversary in Gettier problems, revealing that accidental true beliefs lack the essence of true knowledge. Enter credentism, where knowledge is redefined as justified belief (JB). This paradigm shift highlights the subjective nature of knowledge, emphasizing the fluctuating confidence levels tied to our evolving patterns of understanding. Discover how credentism tackles the evolutionary function of knowledge, framing it as a tool shaped by social and, ultimately, evolutionary utility.

Epistemological paradigms unfold, with credentism as the third level, introducing degrees of confidence as the basis for knowledge. Explore the synthesis of knowledge as epistemic confidence, and embark on a journey of epistemic synthesism, where confidence emerges from the aggregation of justifications. The article invites you to challenge preconceived notions, embracing the yin and yang relationship between knowledge and absurdity. As you navigate the nuanced dance of these forces, be prepared to explore the small circles within the yin and yang, symbols of doubt and possibility that add layers of complexity to the tapestry of human understanding. Get ready to question, challenge, and redefine your understanding of knowledge in this groundbreaking exploration of credentist epistemology."

title: Chinese Philosophy: Suffering brings new abilities
description:
https://transcendentphilos.wixsite.com/website/forum/transcendent-mythology/mengzi-those-who-suffer-have-a-great-mission


English Translation:
"It has been said of old time, when the heavens determine to bestow a great mission unto some person, they must first be tested with distress of the mind, exhaustion of the flesh, hunger of the body, want for material needs, and misfortune on every turn, this so that their heart may develop endurance and firmness of character until they obtain abilities originally not possible."


Chinese Original Version:
天将降大任于斯人也，
Tiān jiāng jiàng dàrèn yú sī rén yě,
必先苦其心志，劳其筋骨，
bì xiān kǔ qí xīnzhì, láo qí jīngǔ,
饿其体肤，空乏其身，
è qí tǐ fū, kōngfá qí shēn, 
行拂乱其所为，所以动心忍性，
xíng fú luàn qí suǒ wéi, suǒyǐ dòngxīn rěn xìng,
曾益其所不能.
zēng yì qí suǒ bùnéng.

title: Chinese TV series with the DEEPEST philosophy?
description:

title: Chinese Philosophy: Suffering brings new abilities (audio 1 ear)
description:
https://transcendentphilos.wixsite.com/website/forum/transcendent-mythology/mengzi-those-who-suffer-have-a-great-mission


English Translation:
"It has been said of old time, when the heavens determine to bestow a great mission unto some person, they must first be tested with distress of the mind, exhaustion of the flesh, hunger of the body, want for material needs, and misfortune on every turn, this so that their heart may develop endurance and firmness of character until they obtain abilities originally not possible."


Chinese Original Version:
天将降大任于斯人也，
Tiān jiāng jiàng dàrèn yú sī rén yě,
必先苦其心志，劳其筋骨，
bì xiān kǔ qí xīnzhì, láo qí jīngǔ,
饿其体肤，空乏其身，
è qí tǐ fū, kōngfá qí shēn, 
行拂乱其所为，所以动心忍性，
xíng fú luàn qí suǒ wéi, suǒyǐ dòngxīn rěn xìng,
曾益其所不能.
zēng yì qí suǒ bùnéng.

title: Why is the Hard Problem of Consciousness so Hard?
description:
***Sorry for my posture - it is due to back pain***

Overview of different ways to express the "hard problem of consciousness" including the "how and why", qualia, dead/alive dichotomy, philosophic zombies, engineering of consciousness, the gap between collisions and consciousness, rock-to-ghost analogy, cosmic consciousness analogy, and the AI machine language red analogy.

Additionally we go over dualism, parsimony, the gap between dualism and panpsychism, ways to measure consciousness, the location of consciousness in the brain, and a theory about the geometry of brain patterns being the key aspect of qualia engineering.  

–––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––

title: Ode to Sophia - the Goddess of Wisdom
description:
Music: Synapse by Shane Ivers - https://www.silvermansound.com
 
FB: https://www.facebook.com/transcendentphilosophy

“Oh, Sophia, thou goddess of wisdom, how I love thy grace and beauty!  I bid thee to stay by my side and inspire me.  Teach me thy ways so that I may walk in thy light.  Though my days be filled with dreary loneliness, the light of thy countenance brighteneth my path.  The love of a thousand women cannot compare to the ecstasy of thine embrace.  The warmth of thy bosom thaws my frigid soul.  Thy kiss lighteth upon my lips and I can speak words of greatness.  The burden of existence is made light by thy smile.  Through thine eyes I can see the happiness and joy of all future generations of mankind.  The beating of thy heart reverberates throughout space-time like a drop in an ocean that spreads outward continually.  One night in thine arms is enough to change the fate of nations.  Oh, that all mankind could see through thine eyes and feel through thy touch!  Then would all hearts beat in harmony to the melody of thy song of wisdom as it echoes throughout the eternities.”
